===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} ''[[leþer]]'', from {{proto|Germanic|leþran}} (compare West Frisian {{term|leare|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|leder}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Leder}}, Swedish {{term|läder|lang=sv}}), from {{etyl|cel-gau}} *''letrom'' (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|lledr}}, {{etyl|ga|-}} {{term|lethar}}), from pre-Celtic *''péltrom'', from {{proto|Indo-European|pel-}} 'to beat'. More at [[anvil]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-leather.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɛðə(r)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# A tough material produced from the [[skin]] of [[animal]]s, by [[tan]]ning or similar process, used e.g. for [[clothing]].
# A piece of the above used for [[polish]]ing.
# (''colloquialism'') A [[cricket]] ball or [[football]].
# (''plural'': '''leathers''') clothing made from the skin of animals, often worn by [[motorcycle]] riders.
# {{baseball}} A good defensive play
#: ''Jones showed good '''leather''' to snare that [[liner]].''

